# Deployment Journey

## Step 1 – Creating the Resource Group

I started by creating a dedicated Resource Group to keep every Azure resource organized.

```bash
az group create \
    --name rag-ai-rg \
    --location eastus
```

Creating a Resource Group first made resource management much easier because everything related to the project lives in one place.

---

## Step 2 – Creating Azure Container Registry

The next step was creating Azure Container Registry.

This registry stores all Docker images used by the application.

```bash
az acr create \
    --resource-group rag-ai-rg \
    --name ragazureacr \
    --sku Premium
```

After creating ACR, I authenticated Docker using Azure CLI and verified that image pushes were working correctly.

---

## Step 3 – Deploying Azure Kubernetes Service

The Kubernetes cluster is the core of the platform.

I enabled Managed Identity and Workload Identity because I wanted the workloads to access Azure services securely without embedding credentials inside the containers.

```bash
az aks create \
    --resource-group rag-ai-rg \
    --name rag-ai-aks \
    --node-count 3 \
    --enable-managed-identity \
    --enable-oidc-issuer
```

Once the cluster was created, I connected kubectl to AKS and verified the worker nodes.

---

## Step 4 – Building Docker Images

The application consists of three independent services.

- Frontend
- Backend API
- Worker

Each component was containerized separately.

```bash
docker build -t backend:v1 .
docker build -t worker:v1 .
docker build -t frontend:v1 ./frontend
```

Separating the services makes scaling much easier because each workload can be scaled independently.

---

## Step 5 – Deploying the Platform

Instead of manually creating Kubernetes objects one by one, I used Helm charts for packaging and Argo CD for GitOps deployment.

Every code change pushed to Git automatically updates the Kubernetes cluster.

This significantly reduces manual deployment effort while improving consistency across environments.

